\newpage


\begin{enumerate}

\item The answers to two counting questions are given below.  Give two
  questions, 1 to match each answer. Comment briefly.
  \begin{enumerate}
  \item  ${12 \choose 4}$
\vfill
  \item  ${12 \choose 4}\cdot P(6,3)={12 \choose 4}\cdot 6\cdot 5\cdot 4$
\vfill
  \end{enumerate}

\item Let $\Omega=\{a,b,c\}$ be a 3-element probability space with
  probability function $P$.
  Is it possible to have two events that are independent and
    mutually exclusive? If so, give an example, and say what the
    probability function $P$ is. If not, explain why not.
\vfill




\item A box contains 3 red and 4 blue marbles, all equally likely to be
  selected on a random draw.  A game of chance consists of 5 consecutive
  draws, replacing the marble after each draw and shaking the box so
  that each marble has the same chance to be drawn on the next draw.
  The questions below refer to the following probability problem about
  this game.
  \begin{quote}
    Problem: Find the chance that exactly 3 of the 5 draws are red marbles.
  \end{quote}

  \begin{enumerate}
  \item Describe a sample space of outcomes for this game.  Say whether
    you use lists or sets, and what objects are elements in your lists
    and sets. 

\vfill
\newpage

\item Count your sample space given in the previous part.  Briefly
  comment on what principle(s) of counting you use.

\vfill

\item Is the probability function on your sample space uniform?  If not,
  choose two outcomes with different probabilities and give those probabilities.  Briefly comment on what
  principle(s) of probability you use.

\vfill

\item Describe the event in your sample space specified by the phrase
  ``get exactly 3 reds in 5 draws''.  Count the size of this event.
  Briefly comment on what principle(s) of counting you use.

\vfill

\item Solve the problem, that is, find the chance that exactly 3 of the
  5 draws are red.  Briefly comment on what principle(s) of probability you use.

\vfill

  \end{enumerate}


\end{enumerate}

